T1  - TRAINING, TURNOVER, AND SEARCH*
AU  - Quercioli, Elena
Y1  - 2005/02/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0020-6598.2005.00312.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 133
EP  - 143
VL  - 46
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0020-6598.2005.00312.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article explores a model of firm-specific training in a job search environment with labor turnover. The main substantive finding is a positive association between training and wages (when dispersed). The article then precisely characterizes how both wage dispersion and firm profitability depend on the flow value b≥ 0 of workers' unmatched time. It is shown that: (i) for all high values b, no equilibrium exists; (ii) for intermediate values b, multiple equilibria arise, where firms earn zero profits, and choose from a general wage distribution; (iii) for all lower values b, there is a unique equilibrium, with firms earning positive profits, and choosing from an atomless set of wages.
ER  - 

